UFW stands for Uncomplicated Firewall. Itâ€™s a user-friendly interface for managing iptables, the powerful but complex firewall tool built into Linux systems.

ðŸ›¡ What UFW Does:

UFW makes it easier to configure a host-based firewall by providing simple command-line options to:

Allow or deny traffic on specific ports
Limit access by IP address
Set default policies
Enable/disable the firewall
Monitor firewall rules

[+] Installation:
# sudo apt install ufw / gufw

[+] Usage:
# sudo ufw -h 
# sudo ufw status 
# sudo ufw enable

[+] Deny some specific traffic:
# sudo ufw deny from [IP] 
# sudo ufw deny from [IP]/24
# sudo ufw deny in on eth0 from [IP]
# sudo ufw allow "samba"

[+] Allow some specific traffic:
# ssudo ufw allow in on eth0 from [IP]
# sudo ufw allow "OpenSSH"
# sudo ufw allow "dns"
# sudo ufw allow "aapache2"
# sudo ufw allow "Nginx FULL"
# sudo ufw app list 

